A field of psychology surrounding the lives of LGBTQIA+ individuals, in particular the diverse range of psychological perspectives and experiences of these individuals. It covers different aspects such as identity development including the 'coming out' process, parenting and family practices and supports for LGBTQIA+ individuals, as well as issues of prejudice and discrimination involving the LGBTQIA+ community.

A perspective on psychology that draws extensively on critical theory. Critical psychologists believe conventional psychology fails to consider how power differences between social classes and groups can impact an individuals or a group's mental and physical well-being. Conventional psychology does this, in part, by explaining behavior at the individual level.
Any of various social norms based on environment.
The idea that metropolitan or urban areas and populations are prioritized over other areas, such as those that are rural or suburban.
A norm and structure in LGBTQIA+ communities in which the metropolitan is prioritized as a mode of acceptance, i.e. the only way of achieving happiness and open existence.
Discrimination based on the environment in which a person or people live, exist, work, etc.

Hostility toward the city as opposed to the country, a simple rejection of the city, or a wish to destroy the city; discrimination against persons seen as belonging to cities. Such hostility and/or discrimination may be individualized or collective. Anti-urbanism may also be interpreted as a philosophy which aims to tackle metronormative ways of life. The phenomenon of anti-urbanism is often linked to urban and/or metropolitan bias.
Biases based on one's environment.
A bias in favor of rural population areas over more concentrated metropolitan population centers.
A bias in favor of concentrated urban population centers over more diffuse rural or suburban population areas.
A bias in favor of concentrated metropolitan population centers over more diffuse rural or suburban population areas.

"[A] means to critically negotiate the relentless urbanisms that often characterize any United States based 'gay imaginary'... in which the city represents a beacon of tolerance and gay community, the country a locus of persecution and gay absence." In this sense, queer anti-urbanism can be thought of as critical opposition to homonormative and metronormative ways of life.
A term sometimes used (mostly in the United States) to refer to Asian persons and Pacific Islanders.
